What does Anno ?
================

Anno is a calendar program that helps to organize your personal dates.
The program sorts userdefined dates chronologically and displays them year
by year in a list. Dates of different actuality are marked by different
configurable colors.

Anno is easy to use. Dates may be changed, deleted or added instantly
without a special editor program. Furthermore Anno calculates weekdays, easter
and advent related holidays for every year from 100 to 3200.

Anno has been programmed in assembler, is rather short (13 K actually)
and doesn't need much memory. Only system libraries are used.
@endnode

@node Requirements


System requirements
===================

Anno needs OS 2.04 (V37) or higher. For localized names of weekdays and
months locale.library V38+ is required. But Anno works without locale.library,
too.

    @{" next " link "Start"}
@endnode

@node Start


Start
=====

Anno can be started from shell or Workbench. If you start it from shell
the following arguments can be given, but it is more comfortable to use
the configuration file @{"ENV:anno.prefs" link "Installation"} to adapt Anno to your needs.

If you prefer to start Anno from Workbench you may also write the arguments
into Anno's icon as ToolTypes.

DATA/K	    provides the name of the data file which contains the dates
	    to be displayed. This is a simple ASCII file which can be
	    written with an editor, but it can be installed by Anno too
	    when you first use it. The format of the data file is explained
	    in the chapter @{"The data file" link "Data"}.

FONT/K	    sets the font to be used, e.g. FONT topaz.font/11.
	    The number after "/" is the font size. The font must be
	    @{i}nonproportional!@{ui}

SCREEN/K    Name of the pubscreen where Anno should appear.
	    Default: DefaultPubScreen, normally Workbench

LEFT/N	    defines the distance from the left edge of the screen to the
	    window.
	    Default: centered

TOP/N	    defines the distance from top of the screen to the window.
	    Default: Window appears above the middle of the screen

COLUMNS/N   Number of characters of one text line in the window, determines
	    window width.
	    Default: COLUMNS=64

LINES/N     Number of text lines in the window, determines window highth.
	    Default: LINES=25

PENS/K	    defines the pens to be used for the display. Anno uses 7 colors
	    to mark events of different actuality. If your Workbench has
	    enough pens Anno may look rather colorful.
	    If you don't specify PENS default colors will be used.

	    The pens must be specified in a special order, each separated
	    from the next by a dot or comma. If you have a Workbench with
	    4 colors, you can use pen numbers 0-3, with 8 colors 0-7 and
	    with 256 colors 0-255.

	    If you don't know which pen produces which color use a palette
	    program like FullPalette. Now the meaning of the different
	    pens:

	    order    meaning		       default (Palette)
	    ---------------------------------------------------------
	      1      normal text	       Text
	      2      normal background	       Background
	      3      background for	       Bright Edges
		     daily events
	      4      background for events     Bright Edges
		     of current day
	      5      text color for events     Active Window Titles
		     of current week
	      6      background vor events     Active Window Titlebar
		     of current week
	      7      background for events     Active Window Titlebar
		     of next week

	    With a Workbench of the 4 standard colors the sequence would
	    be 1.0.2.2.1.3.3 (black.gray.white.white.black.blue.blue).
	    If you are satisfied with this you need not use PENS.
	    Example for 256 available colors:
	    PENS 1.19.109.2.1.168.170

YEAR/N	    determines which year is indicated after start of the program.
	    The years 2000 - 2099 may be abbreviated as 0 - 99. YEAR 0 is thus
	    2000. In this way the oldest year that can be indicated is the
	    year 100. The upper limit is year 3200.

	    If no year has been indicated Anno shows the dates of the
	    current year. It is, however, no problem to shift from there
	    into different years.

	    It is important to know that according to the selected year
	    the days of the week and the dates related to Easter are
	    calculated either according to the Gregorian or to the Julian
	    calendars. The limit is the year 1583 from when on the Gregorian
	    calendar was exclusively valid in all catholic countries.
	    It was introduced in October 1582.

    @{" next " link "Installation"}

@endnode

@node Installation


Installation
============

The programm may be copied to any place whatever, e.g. to C: or into the
WBStartUp directory. Furthermore 2 files are needed which Anno looks for
after start:

    - the configuration file ENV:anno.prefs (additionally the tooltypes
      will be read, when started from workbench)
    - the data file that is to say the file which contains the dates to be
      shown.

If no data file has as yet been installed an almost empty window appears
which merely shows the date of the actual day.

Both files are normal ASCII files and can be installed with an editor.
The configuration file anno.prefs must also be copied to @{b}ENVARC:@{ub} in order
to be available after each system start.

The entries in anno.prefs correspond to the Shell arguments:

		@{" DATA    " link "Start"12}
		@{" FONT    " link "Start"18}
		@{" PENS    " link "Start"36}
		@{" SCREEN  " link "Start"22}
		@{" LEFT    " link "Start"25}
		@{" TOP     " link "Start"29}
		@{" LINES   " link "Start"36}
		@{" COLUMNS " link "Start"32}

For each entry you have to use a new line. Comments may be inserted at
any place whatever after a semicolon.

;example for anno.prefs
DATA=s:anno.data	;Name/path of the @{"data file" link "Data"}
FONT=topaz.font/11
PENS=1.0.2.2.2.3.2	;for a Workbench of 4 colors

    @{" next " link "Data"}

@endnode

@node Data


The data file
=============

This is the file that contains the dates one wants to be reminded of.
It may be written with an editor, one may, however, also enter date by
date via the GUI of Anno. There is no need to enter the dates chronologically,
they will be sorted by Anno.

For each date a separate line has to be written which starts with a date
and then after a blank space continues with the text related to the date
(start of holidays, meeting with friends, dental appointment...).
This text may be of any length. Lines that are too long to fit into the window
will be wrapped at word bounderies.

Characters with a special meaning
---------------------------------

You may force linewrapping by using the sign "|".

Example:

24.12.07 Chrismas Eve|15 h prepare the presents|16 h distribution of presents

This would produce the following display:

 Mon 24-Dec  Chrismas Eve
	     15 h prepare presents
	     16 h distribution of presents

Another character with a special effect is "!". If placed @{b}at the beginning@{ub}
of a line after the date the following text will be displayed in boldface.

Example: Tue !Letters to mail-box
Result:  Tue 1-Mar @{b}Letters to mailbox@{ub}

You may adopt the following list of holidays as a basis for your personal
data file. The meaning of the used date formats will be explained in chapter
@{"Date types" link "Types"}.

;--------------------------------- clip -----------------------------
1.1.	  New Year
6.1.	  Epiphany
14.2.	  Valentine
E-48	  Carnival Monday
E-47	  Mardi Gras
E-46	  Ash Wednesday
E-7	  Palm Sunday
E-3	  Maundy Thursday
E-2	  Good Friday
E+0	  Easter Sunday
1.5.	  Labor Day
2.Sun.5.  Mother's day
E+39	  Ascension of Christ
E+49	  Whitsunday
E+60	  Feast of Corpus Christi
5.Sun.3   +1h, summer time
5.Sun.10  -1h, winter time
5.Thu.11. Thanksgiving Day
A-14	  Memorial Day
A-11	  Penitential and Prayer Day
A-7	  Death Sunday
A+0	  1.Advent
A+7	  2.Advent
A+14	  3.Advent
A+21	  4.Advent
24.12.	  Christmas Eve
25.12.	  Christmas Day
31.12.	  New Year's Eve
2.Tue	  Microsoft Patchday
;--------------------------------- clip -----------------------------

    @{" next " link "Types"}

@endnode

@node Types


Date types
==========

Anno accepts 5 types of dates where the first four ones can be varied
in length (see below):

    - normal date consisting of day, month and year
    - date related to Easter
    - date related to 1st Advent
    - date related to a weekday
    - daily date

The components of a date must be separated from each other by any
nonnumerical character except the space character. The space serves as
separator between date and the corresponding text. So, for example "1st of
may 2007" may be entered as follows:

    1.5.07 or 1.5.2007 or 01-05-07 oder 1/5/07 etc.

The order day/weekday - month - year is obligatory and cannot be varied.
Day or weekday have always to be specified, month and year may be omitted.
The more components of a date you omit the more often it appears in the
displayed list:

    date with year    -> appears only in the specified year
    date without year -> appears annually
    day only	      -> appears monthly
    weekday only      -> appears weekly
    "*"               -> appears daily

In the following survey some abbreviations are used:
    d = day of the month (1-31)
    m = number of the month (1-12)
    y = year
    E = Easter Sunday
    A = 1st Advent
    wd= weekday, abbreviatedą
    Today=current day

ą)
The abbreviations to be used for weekdays are those used by Anno in the
main window. If localisation is not possible (OS less than V38) you have
to use the english abbreviations (Mon,Tue...Sun) else those of your
own language.


			@{b}Survey of date types@{ub}
			--------------------


Date type	Format			Comment
=========================================================================
Normal date	d.m.y			also d-m-y or d/m/y possible

Examples	23.3.07 		Appears only in 2007
					The weekday is calculated by Anno

		1.5.			The year has been omitted here,
		24.12.			appears therefore every year.
					Holydays, anniversaries etc. with
					constant dates can be defined in
					this way.

		15.			Month and year have been omitted,
					appears therefore monthly.
					Weekday and month are substituted
					by Anno. Will be displayed only
					in the list of the current year
					and from Today on.
		31.			If d > length of current month
					then d is the last day of month:
					31.Jan, 28./29.Feb(if leap year),
					30.Apr, 31.May...
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Date with	n.wd.m.y		means: nth weekday in month m
weekday 				and year y

Examples	1.Thu.10.07		First Thursday in October 2007

		1.Thu.10.		First Thursday in October of every
					year

		5.Sun.3.		Last Sunday in March of every year
					The last weekday of a month can be
					achieved by setting n=5 or higher.

		2.Tue			2nd Tuessday of every month from
					Today on. If this weekday has
					passed away in the current month
					next month will be taken.

		Wed			every Wednesday
					If Wednesday has already passed
					away in the current week Wednesday
					of the next week will be displayed.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Daily		*			appears every day but only in the
					current year's list and always above
					Today.
					This format can be used for urgent
					affairs which must be done as soon
					as possible (to-do list)

Example 	* buy new shoes
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Easter		E+/-n.y 		means: Easter Sunday plus or minus
dependant				n days in year y


Examples	E+0.07			Easter Sunday in 2007
		E+0			Easter Sunday of every year
		E+1			Easter Monday "    "    "
		E-2			Good Friday   "    "    "
		E+49			Whitsun       "    "    "
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Advent		A+/-n.y 		means: 1st Advent +/- n days
dependant				in year y

Examples	A+7.07			2nd Advent in 2007

		A+21			4th Advent of every year

All this may appear rather complicated but unfortunately it cannot be
done any easier than that. Furthermore you are likely to use the majority
of the data types either not at all or only once when installing the
data file.

    @{" next " link "Interface"}

@endnode

@node "Interface"


User interface
==============

Anno opens a window that displays the dates of the selected year as an
ordered list. In case that no data file exists as yet only one single line
with the date of the actual day and text "Today" is presented.

If the list of dates of a year doesn't fit into the window you may go through
with the cursor keys or with the scroll gadget on right hand edge. If the year
displayed is the current one the segment with the actual dates will be
presented in the following order:

    daily dates (todo-list)
    today's dates
    dates of the current week
    dates of the following week

In case that there are no dates for today a line with the current date
will be produced internally.

@{b}Use of mouse buttons@{ub}

1. Click with left mouse button -> Edit, delete a date
-------------------------------
Click on the line you want to modify. A requester will pop up which lets you
choose among "Delete", "Edit" and "Cancel". You may edit the date or the text
of an entry or both. When the modification is done and you press Return the
modified entry will be shown immediately in the window and the word "modified"
appears in the window title bar.

2. Shift-click with left mouse button -> Swap/Move lines
-------------------------------------
The order of lines @{i}with the same date@{ui} can be changed by shift-clicking
on a line. This line will then move one position up, the line above will
move one position down. Repeatedly shift-clicking on a line moves it to the
top, repeatedly shift-clicking beneath a line moves it to the bottom.

3. Click with right mouse button -> Show difference
--------------------------------
When clicking on an entry a requester pops up showing:

    - date
    - number of the day in the year currently presented
    - number of the week in the year currently presented ą)
    - difference in days to current day (today)

ą) The weeknumber is calculated according ISO 8601 standard. This standard
   says that a week starts on Monday. The first week of the year is thatone
   that consists at least of 4 days. If it is shorter it belongs to the last
   week of the foregoing year. So, it may happen that the first week of a year
   has the number 52 or the last week of a year has the number 1.

@{b}The Gadgets@{ub}


   [<]		1 year back

   [Add date]	add a new date
		You have to enter a date and - separated by space - the
		corresponding text. The date must be in a format accepted
		by Anno

   [Find date]	find a string in the data file
		The search is case insensitive. If found the corresponding
		entry is shown and you can choose among "Next", "Show"
		and "Cancel". If you opt for "Show" the segment of the
		year's list will be presented to which the respective date
		belongs.

   [<year>]	This field shows the year whose dates are actually presented.
		After clicking on this field or pressing the key "Y"
		you can enter another year.

   [O] = Open	open another data file

   [P] = Print	enables the printing or saving of the list of dates for
		the year presented. In order to print you have to enter
		"PRT:" else a file name. If your printer is online PRT:
		is the default.
		If the year shown is the current one you can restrict
		the printing to the most actual dates (daily, today,
		this week, next week). Click on [actual dates only] or press
		RAmiga-a to achieve this else the whole year will be printed.

   [M]		Two-month overview
		Shows calendars of the current month and the following one.
		Dates occuring in the year's list (today, this week, next
		week) are marked by the appropriate background colors.
		Exception: Dates after next week are marked by the color for
		daily events.

   [D]		find out weekday or date
		You have to enter a date according to the date formats
		accepted by Anno. Example: "e+0.01" gives the date of
		Easter Sunday 2001 (Sun 15-04-2001).
		Additionally the Julian date (for days from 5th October 1582
		on) and the difference to current day will be calculated.

   [I]		Information about
		- the data file currently loaded
		- number of total dates in this file
		- number of dates in the year indicated:
		-----------------------------
		- daily dates
		- today's dates
		- dates of the current week
		- dates of the following week

   [?]		Version, author and address

   [*]		jumps to the current year and shows the section with
		daily dates (to-do list).

   [>]		1 year on

Every gadget has its key equivalent which is identical with the first
character of the gadget text.

With the keys Q and Esc you may leave the program. If datas have been
modified you'll be asked whether you want to save them.

   @{b}Further key commands:@{ub}

   Help 		table of key commands and mouse button actions
   .			search as with key "F"
   Y			enter another year and display it
   Cursor up		one line up
   Cursor down		one line down
   Cursor left		to the beginning of the year's list
   Cursor right 	to the end of the year's list
   Space		one page down
   Shift-Cursor down	same as Space
   Backspace		one page back
   Shift-Cursor up	same as Backspace

All key commands which move through the year's list automatically switch
to the next/previous year when the bottom/top of the list is reached.

